##The outbreak of the epidemic has intensified social tensions in Iran and Chinese have fled

Weixin caijingEleven

The function introduction by "CAIJING" Magazine Company Industry Report team to create, discuss the success or failure of the enterprise, explore the rise and fall of the industry, promote sunshine business

The new crown adds to the woes of Iran's economy, which is under American sanctions, and adds fuel to already simmering social rivalries, and could be the most dangerous moment for the Iranian regime in the 40 years of the Islamic Revolution

By Leo Liszt

Mark | editor

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Iran's new coronary pneumonia epidemic is "explosive" spread. On 19 February, Iran reported the first two confirmed cases of new coronavirus pneumonia and two confirmed patients died on the same day. As of March 5, the cumulative number of officially confirmed cases in Iran has reached 2,922, of which 92 have died, representing a mortality rate of about 3.14 per cent. The mortality rate in Hubei at about the same stage was 3.24% (February 1) .

The response from the Iranian government and people has been "slow" , as people continue to live at the same pace as in the past, while the lack of medical resources and the lack of guidance from the state-run media have led Chinese living in Iran to embark on a "flight from Tehran" .

The outbreak has not only affected the Iranian population, but also the system of government. As of March 3, at least 23 of the 290 members of Iran's parliament, or 8 percent, had been diagnosed with the infection. The parliament has been suspended indefinitely, and members have been asked not to meet with the public. In addition, Iran's Vice Minister of Health, Vice President, Minister of Industry and other senior officials have been confirmed, Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei a senior adviser died of new pneumonia.

The fear is that if Iran gets out of hand, the entire Middle East will be in jeopardy. As of March 3, at least 10 countries in the Middle East have reported imported cases from Iran, and Beijing, China, on February 29 also reported two confirmed cases from the Shiite holy city of Qom in Iran. Both are Chinese nationals.

Facing the increasingly serious situation, the leader Khamenei on March 3 asked the army to assist the Ministry of Health to combat the epidemic. The Iranian government is considering mobilizing 300,000 soldiers and volunteers, according to the Al Jazeera. On the same day, Iran announced the provisional release of 54,000 prisoners to prevent further transmission of the new coronavirus. Construction has also begun on an Iranian version of the Vulcan Mountain Hospital in the central city of Yazd.

For the Iranian regime, the outbreak has further inflamed already high levels of public discontent, adding to an already difficult economy under severe U.S. sanctions, this may be the most dangerous moment in the 40 years of the Islamic Revolution.

To escape Tehran

"I just want to get back to China as soon as possible, " Zhang Yihao, a Chinese graduate student at Tehran University, told Caijing. "There are so many foreigners trying to flee Iran that the rooms for exit visas are packed every day. ".

Given Iran's medical conditions, and the lack of attention from officials and the public, Zhang believes the epidemic is out of control. "When I think of the days when the city was closed in Wuhan, when one bed was hard to find, I am even more determined to go home. "

Every day, the number of new cases reported by the Iranian government is soaring, but many living in Iran believe the real situation will only get worse.

In order to avoid contact with people, Zhang preferred to walk when applying for an exit visa. The sweetmeats restaurants, restaurants and banks along the way were the same as usual, no one wears a mask.

Among the foreigners who fled Tehran, the Chinese are more sensitive to the outbreak, not only raising their own chartered flights home, but also actively coordinating with the Chinese Embassy in Iran. On the afternoon of March 4,146 Chinese citizens from Tehran arrived at Lanzhou Airport on Flight CZ3002 of China Southern Airlines under the coordination of the embassy and were immediately sent to the Reserve Hospital of Lanzhou New District for observation under isolation.

Chen Chun (not his real name) , who has lived in Tehran for a decade and now works for a travel agency, chose not to leave, but to move with his family to the outskirts of Tehran to escape the heat. "Now the city has become a disaster area, the suburbs, after all, have a small population density and the epidemic is much lighter. We stock up on grain and try not to go out, but we can withstand it for a while, " Chen told Caijing.

"My feeling is that the Chinese are panicking, but the Iranians are taking their time, " Chen told his fellow Iranians from time to time about the horrors of the new pneumonia, urging them to wear masks, wash their hands frequently and buy disinfectant, which they felt was an overreaction.

On television, Iranian officials also created an atmosphere in which the outbreak was not a big deal, telling people to go to work normally and to take regular precautions. They even tell people there's no need to wear masks. Only medical personnel and patients wear them. So even in Qom, where the epidemic is at its worst, masks are few and far between.

In recent days, Tehran's subways, streets, schools and other public areas began sprinkler disinfection operations. But according to Chen, "disinfection of public areas is far less effective than a mask. "

To urge Iranians to pay attention to the epidemic, Tan Pin Pin, a phd student in the Chinese Department at Peking University, volunteered to form a mutual aid group to fight the epidemic by producing a Persian language propaganda video and translating epidemic prevention materials, to make the Iranian people aware that the disease is highly contagious. Tan Pin Pin told CAIJING that the group involved not only many volunteer translators, but also embassy staff, Iranian scholars and the media in Iraq.

Iranian customs also pose a threat to the spread of the epidemic. Family values are high in Iran, and family members who used to live together in the Hitotsu Yane no Shita now live close to each other, moving around a lot and having family gatherings every weekend. In addition, Iran is a religious and political country, where people gather in mosques for Friday prayers, practices that greatly increase the risk of transmission of the virus.

As the outbreak escalated, the Iranian government stepped up its response.

Social and political crisis intensified

"The impact of the epidemic on Iran's economy, society and political situation has reached the most critical juncture since the Islamic Revolution in 1979, and is no less serious than the iran-iran war, " Yin Gang of West Asia, a member of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, told Caijing.

In May 2018, after the United States unilaterally withdrew from the Iran nuclear agreement, it imposed unprecedented and severe sanctions on Iran, which severely damaged Iran's economy and caused its GDP to decline by about 9 percent in 2019. The crisis has been further exacerbated by the outbreak of the new crown disease, which Yin predicted will cause GDP to fall by more than 20% this year.

The impact of the US sanctions on Iran is all-round. Not only has the US dollar settlement channel for Iran's foreign trade been cut off, Iran's international trade has been basically paralyzed, and the value of its own currency has been substantially depreciated. It has also caused Iran's oil exports to once "clear zero" , that's caused a huge drop in revenue. In just a few years, the standard of living of the Iranian people has clearly regressed.

Chen has a personal experience of this, "soaring prices are 'visible' to the naked eye, today a price of 10,000 rials things tomorrow into 20,000, a monthly salary to go to the supermarket is almost gone. "

Iranians have been forced to buy foreign currency on the black market to protect their currency against a sharp fall in the value of their own currency. "Many Iranians around me are afraid to hold large amounts of their own currency in their hands, but the more they rush to buy foreign currency, the more their currency depreciates and they are trapped in a vicious circle, " Chen said.

Even with the severity of the outbreak, Iranians are reluctant to give up their jobs because they are too scared to save. Many Iranians live on a day-to-day basis, earning only enough to cover the day's expenses, and when they can not work, many are immediately hungry.

In July 2019, Iran introduced a unilateral visa-free policy for Chinese citizens, leading to a doubling of the number of Chinese tourists. Many Chinese had originally listed Iran as a destination for the Spring Festival holiday, which the country's wine, tourism and catering industry also hoped to take advantage of, but the sudden outbreak of the new crown has brought tourism to the freezing point.

The outbreak has exacerbated Iran's already inflamed social tensions. The results of Iran's parliamentary elections on February 21st bear this out. The ruling reformists won just 20 seats, according to the Ministry of Interior of the Islamic Republic of Iran, while the Conservatives won a resounding victory, taking 221 seats out of a total of 290, including all 30 seats in the capital, Tehran. The turnout was 42.57 per cent, the lowest since the Islamic Revolution in 1979, and 25.4 per cent in the capital.

"there is widespread dissatisfaction with the reformist rulers and the economic situation in Iran, " Jin Liangxiang, an associate fellow at the West asia-africa Research Center of the Shanghai Institute of International Studies, told Caijing.

The authorities'failure to contain the outbreak has further stoked public discontent. Many people believe the government is underreporting the number of confirmed cases, and the Mujahid has even spread rumors that the number of cases has reached 60,000. "The Iranian government may not have covered it up, they just don't have access to the real data, but we can be sure that there are more real patient data than the government has published, " Jin said.

In January, 176 Iranians were killed when the popular Sulejmani was assassinated by the United States, following a tepid response from the authorities and the "accidental" destruction of an UAC passenger plane, has exacerbated tensions between Iran's reformist regime and its people. In this parliamentary election, the Guardian Council even rejected the reformist candidate list.

"for ordinary people, trust in the current government has hit rock bottom. For the top, Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei is old and all forces have been very active recently, " said Yin, ali Khamenei faces not just an epidemic, but the worst moment in the 40 year history of the Islamic revolution, when unrest could strike at any time.

However, Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei now has the ability to mobilize state resources to deal with the epidemic, such as mobilizing the Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution to build a new field hospital in Qom, where the disease is most severe, Yin said, it shows that the authorities are still relatively strong in their ability to control and mobilize the army.

Yin also believes that the Iranian people and high-level are sober, once political turmoil in Iran, does not mean that the United States will relax sanctions on Iran.

It has little effect on the international oil price

The epidemic in Iran is spreading across the Middle East, where at least 10 countries had confirmed cases imported from Iran as of March 3.

"If the epidemic in Iran gets out of control, the whole Middle East region will be in great danger, " said Jin, adding that Iran, with a population of 80 million, is at a crossroads of the Eurasian Transportation Line and has been a regional political, economic and Cultural Center since ancient times.

Iran's position in the Middle East is similar to Wuhan's "thoroughfare of nine provinces" in China. To the West and Iraq, Syria and other countries, east and Afghanistan, Pakistan and other countries, north and Azerbaijan, Turkmenistan and south and Arabian Peninsula have very close personnel exchanges.

Because of American sanctions, Iran's foreign trade can only be done through third countries, which further increases Iranian mobility abroad. "Dubai is an important transit point for Iranian businessmen to do business, and normal business exchanges are very frequent in normal times. Plus, middle and upper-class people who fled Iran due to the epidemic choose Dubai as a temporary refuge, " Zhang said. Throughout the Middle East, there are many more transit points for Iranian businessmen.

The worst affected city, Qom, is a Shiite holy city, with worshippers from all over the world visiting Qom, posing a huge risk of spreading the disease. On February 29th Beijing discovered two confirmed cases imported from Iran, both from Qom.

The great risk of epidemic spreading in Iran has aroused the attention of the whole world. China sent a team of experts to Iran on February 29 with some aid to help control the epidemic there, and the U.S. Treasury Department issued an exemption on February 27, iran can trade humanitarian goods through the Central Bank of Iran.

Since 1979, Iran's theocratic regime has consistently pursued an expansionist foreign policy, and its frequent actions in the Middle East have not only actively exported the Islamic revolution to expand the Shi'ite power, efforts to create a "Shi'ite Arc" connecting Iran, Iraq, Syria and Lebanon have also involved frequent religious and trade exchanges with the Shi'ite forces they support.

Yin Gang believes that at present, Iran in the Middle East three directions of force, Iraq and Syria in two directions are shrinking state, only Yemen "Houthi armed forces" in the offensive state, but Iran's national strength can not afford military spending. "The Iranian authorities have already come to the edge of having to adjust after 40 years of external ideological and military exports. If they do not shrink, the contradictions created for the surrounding countries will bite back on them, " Yin said.

The spread of the Iranian epidemic to the Middle East will have an impact on the international oil market is also the focus of attention.

"The impact from Iran itself is not big, because under U.S. sanctions, Iran can not export even a drop of oil, " Wang Nengquan, a principal researcher at the Center for Economic and technological research of Sinochem, told CAIJING, oil fields in the Middle East are mostly desert, sparsely populated and highly automated, and the new crown disease will not have an impact on oil supplies in those countries.

Wang Nengquan believes that the current impact of international oil prices is still a sharp decline in demand. "The international oil market is already an oversupply market, and even if the supply of oil in the Middle East is affected, the increase in production in Russia and the US will be able to balance supply. "

Since the outbreak, Brent Crude has fallen from $65.98 a barrel on Jan. 20 to $49.92 on Feb. 28. Wit Crude fell to $45.27 a barrel on Feb. 28 from $59.35 a barrel on Jan. 20, its biggest weekly drop in 11 years.

In 2019, China imported more than 500 million tons of crude oil, and its dependence on foreign oil rose to 72 percent. Its oil consumption reached 690 million tons, accounting for 14.5 percent of the world's total consumption. The new crown outbreak has had a huge impact on China, the world's largest importer of crude oil and the second largest consumer of oil. As the outbreak spreads to oil-importing countries such as Japan and South Korea, the impact on the world's oil demand will widen, reflected in oil prices, which have plummeted since February 20.

Global oil consumption will grow by only 825,000 bpd in 2020, the International Energy Agency said in its oil market report, published in February, that was 365,000 barrels a day lower than the forecast at the start of the year, the slowest pace of growth since 2011. IHS, a leading international energy consultancy, forecasts that year-on-year growth in global oil consumption in the first quarter of this year will fall to-500,000 b / d from an earlier estimate of 600,000 b / d, it was the second negative growth since the onset of the global financial crisis in 2008.

On March 5, Brent Crude fell 0.28 percent to $50.98 and WTI crude fell 0.24 percent to $46.67.

The writer is a reporter for CAIJING
